SIMPLE: society
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Society
<hw>So*ci"e*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Societies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>societas</ets>,
fr. <ets>socius</ets> a companion: cf. F.
<ets>soci⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Social</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The relationship of men to one another when associated
in any way; companionship; fellowship; company.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Her loved
<xex>society</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is <qex>society</qex> where none intrudes⟦br⟧
By the deep sea, and music in its roar.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Connection; participation; partnership.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The meanest of the people and such as have the least
<qex>society</qex> with the acts and crimes of kings.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A number of persons associated for any temporary or
permanent object; an association for mutual or joint usefulness,
pleasure, or profit; a social union; a partnership; <as>as, a missionary
<ex>society</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The persons, collectively considered, who live in
any region or at any period; any community of individuals who are united
together by a common bond of nearness or intercourse; those who
recognize each other as associates, friends, and
acquaintances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Specifically, the more cultivated portion of any
community in its social relations and influences; those who mutually
give receive formal entertainments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Society of Jesus</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Jesuit</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Society verses</b></col> <ety>[a translation of F. <ets>vers
de soci⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</ets>]</ety>, <cd>the lightest kind of lyrical
poetry; verses for the amusement of polite society.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Socinian</ent>⟦br⟧
